11pt">Newcastle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> route for at least 5 return journeys per week between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Longframlington</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Morpeth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, mostly for work or to connect to other destinations, so I have been able to observe all of the changes on this route since 1971.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.3 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I am submitti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng this evidence because I have full awareness of how </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">important </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the bus service is for we passengers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in all aspects of life, and not just to access shops and basic services.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Anyone not a regular rural bus user has no conception of this, as is reflected by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> policies and implementation for rural bus services .</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Also I think that the best hope for rural public transport is to enable a proper </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">network</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">run profitably</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, in recent years </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">hindered by deteriorating communication with existing passengers and la</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ck of contact with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">potential</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> passengers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, largely because of  the constraints of funding structures.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Profitable and appropriate running of public transport in rural areas is hindered by looking at the funding of each route in isolation, instead of examining it as part of an effective and usable public transport </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">network</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sources:</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fellow passengers </span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> weekly “Northumberland Gazette”</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">observation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Longframlington</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Parish Council meetings, and information which the clerk forwards to me – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">luckily our parish council is keenly interested in public transport</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">attending public meetings about transport and Coun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ty Council north area meetings when work shifts/public transport/lifts from councillors allow me to get there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and home again afterwards</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">searching the County Council website when work shifts/bus times/library opening times allow me to get a meaningful sessi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on on the library computer in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Morpeth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">How do government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Though there were surveys in previous decades, in the last nine years, despite making </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">minimu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, five ret</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">urn journeys per week between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Longframlington</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Morpeth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,  I have only seen one County Council survey, in spring 2011, and one done by a national organization, though I have heard that another was done this spring driver about a specific proposed change t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o our timetable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our parish council has asked for people to notify them of their public transport needs via our parish newsletter, as has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rothbury</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thropton</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,  and upper </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Coquetdale</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but until very recently, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Longhorsley</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the other main village on our bus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> route did not have such a publication.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our weekly, “Northumberland Gazette” covers public transport, publishing a paragraph or two during a  consultation, but usually at the very end of the consultation period.  Is this due to tardy dissemination of i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nformation by the County Council, or to editorial policy.? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Consultation documents are quite complex, and so only really useable online.  An unusually high proportion of bus passengers probably don’t have access to computers, particularly in rural area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s lacking in broadband and decent mobile phone signals, leaving paper documents available at libraries. If people rely on public transport, they might only get to the nearest place with a library one day a week for an hour or two to do essential tasks, so </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would not have time to peruse and respond to a consultation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At a public meeting in Felton, I think in October 2011, about cutting bus services to Newton-on-the -Moor and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Swarland</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, attended by  councillors, council officers, and Arriva representatives </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, it was stated that one of the main ways for determining passenger demand was counting the ticket numbers on services. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local users replied that this could only be done on services which existed, and it did nothing for people needing a bus service which cu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rrently didn’t exist, especially if they had to get a lift to the nearest bus route, often a great distance away</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Though  common practice in urban public transport surveys is  to ask people how far and how they travel to and from the service being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">surveyed, this is not done in Northumberland.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Most regular passengers using weekly passes suspect that they are waved onto the bus without being counted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On regular drivers who know the route and passengers well.  Their employers probably don’t make </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enough use of their local knowledge, and could run a better service if they did. It is only because of these drivers’ personal dedication that this service operates effectively.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.7.i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I arrived back in Northumberland in time to see the five year Local Tra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nsport Plan 2006-2011 apparently voted in by the County Council before the consultation period ended. In autumn 2010, having discovered the name of the Commercial Manager at Arriva, I prepared for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">forthcoming 2011 Local Transport Plan by giving out add</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ress cards with the Arriva manager’s name and head office address in Sunderland to anyone who I heard making a comment about the state of the bus service, hoping that it might encourage the decision-makers to pay more attention to our needs and experiences</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  I was much surprised by the number of people who later told me that they had written letters, even those who had said “they won’t listen to us anyway”.  Apparently the Arriva management also got a surprise.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ii  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Later, questionnaires were distributed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to passengers on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rothbury</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and A1 routes in Northumberland, and collated in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">EVIDENCE BASE FOR THE NORTHUMBERLAND LOCAL TRANSPORT  2011-2026, giving the impression of a howl of anguish from passengers.  There was no publicity about this questionnaire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> on any of the buses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and it was mostly distributed by passengers who got further copies of it themselves</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and distributed it to everyone they could either on the buses or door-to-door.  Even so, I later heard from many passengers who had still had no idea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that a consultation was taking place.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">iii  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Presusmably</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">  this was because, as a subsidised service, Arriva ran it under contract for the County Council, and it  did not cover operating consultations or publicity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">It is probably not in Arriva’s interests </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to facilitate a profitable and effective service if they can get money by contracting to run a service for  the County Council without investing  in market research or promotion.  Few County Council resources available to do this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On “THE BOTTOM LINE” ON B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BC RADIO 4 ON 19/11/11, I HEARD DAVID MARTIN, CHIEF EXECUTIVE OF ARRIVA UK appeared to say </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">taht</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">there was no money in running public transport services, but Arriva forecast healthy growth by getting  money for running services for councils.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Apparent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly the RECENT QUESTIONNAIRE FOR THE FEASIBILITY STUDY FOR THE PROPOSED REINTRODUCTION OF REGULAR BUS SERVICES BETWEEN ALWINTON AND ALNWICK VIA ROTHBURY BY A NEW COMPANY</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, SPIRITBUSES OF ROTHBURY, has uncovered a huge and desperate demand,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> exemplified by sev</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eral of we potential passengers getting a supply of questionnaires and voluntarily distributed them on buses, and door-to-door.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:7.5pt 7.5pt 7.5pt 0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">See</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">my submission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to the NORTHUMBERLAND CORE STRATEGY 2015-2030 PREFERRED OPTIONS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CONSULTATION,  TRANSPORT SECTION,  QUEST</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ION 43:  </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:7.5pt 7.5pt 7.5pt 0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">To base a planning strategy on a vision where the majority of the county is rural, but “where the use of public transport for the journey to work and to school is considered socially necessary but is not commercially viable, the local authority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">ay</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> provide revenue support for services”[Northumberland Economic Strategy p.23] is LUDICROUS.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:7.5pt 7.5pt 7.5pt 0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">In the Local Transport Plan 2011-2026 Strategy Document there are 17 principle elements of the new bus strategy, but </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">none of them mention working with or involvin</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">g the LOCAL BUSINESSES WHOSE EMPLOYEES AND CUSTOMERS ARE USERS OF THE BUS SERVICE, and who might wish for more bus use in order to free up the oversubscribed car parking spaces for a larger number of customers, and a better network of buses to attract more</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> tourists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(e.g. Dutch tourists, 7% of whom expect to use public transport, our nearest neighbours on the ferry)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4)  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">isolated communities?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many special interest groups such as the elderly, frail and vulnerable, and to some extent, young people, are probably very much on the County Council’s radar, and quite a large proportion of available resources are put into sup</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">porting the introduction and operation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">community buses, but these are often only usable for people who are in a position to book in advance in quite small time-slots. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">These, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the excellent car-share schemes implemented by the County Council, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">are not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> suitable for the growing number of people who are struggling to afford a car to get to work, or look for work, and who are increasingly expected to work unusual shifts or at short notice, or both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(zero hours contracts etc.), or who simply want to reduce g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lobal warming by using public transport </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Teenagers seem to be the least informed about changes to bus timetables etc., though public transport has been one of the main campaigning issues of the National Youth Parliament for 2 years running, and youngsters are readily in touch via social media.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Probably an effective route for communicating with them has not been established.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Apparently no recognition that rural communities have a strong tradition and basis in cultural and family links, which needs to be supported by public transport </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(especial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly in the absence of accessible computer services and tuition).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">It isn’t just about taking people into town centres to access increasingly centralised services which have been withdrawn from rural areas.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">It is about allowing people to be able to continue </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">seeing and supporting relatives and friends in neighbouring communities, get to family graves to tend them, recognising that sick people don’t just need medical services, but visitors as well </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(e.g. no Sunday services)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, allowing access to local meetings so </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">that they are not excluded from democracy, and local cultural events and activities to maintain the cohesion of the community </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For some people living on their own, or whose partners are in hospital, their fellow passengers and the bus-drivers can be their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">most important source of company and support.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Buses are a good and rare meeting place for different sections of the community who might not otherwise meet </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e.g. young and old, native and newcomer, people with and without children,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">What are the mai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">n challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities?  How can these challenges be overcome?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Communicating</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with passengers and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> potential</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> passengers (see section 3)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and, for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">day-to-day service </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">changes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, recognition from e.g. Arriva, who say that we can use </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Facebook</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or Twitter, that an unusually high proportion of their passengers don’t have access to or knowledge of these, and many of the most essential journeys are outside of office hours. Arriv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a’s number for enquiries is only open during office hours, with no numbers for “local” depots. Their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Facebook</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> page is only updated during office hours.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are no information offices on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thropton</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> route outside of Newcastle.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Accurately establishing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the need.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">People have had to give up going to places, make unreliable or inefficient ad hoc arrangements, or get a car when finances or environmental principles make it preferable that they did not.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If a new service is put in place, especially if it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not publicised, or has not been properly researched to make sure that it best fits peoples’ needs, it takes some time for people to find out about and transfer back to trusting and relying on public transport.  If , as usual it has been a trial period of o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nly a year, there is not time to build up a base of new and previous customers, and the service is then irrevocably cut due to “lack of demand”.  (Many passengers have concluded that this is probably one of the main objectives when designing “trial periods</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e.g. the recent history of the Newton-on-the-Moor and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Swarland</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> bus service, which was no use for workers, and only catered for a small section of the community before it was cut altogether.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rough roads and reliability in winter – better </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">integration with highways </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">depts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – ensuring better gritting times, passing places, and parking /dumping spaces for snow so that cars aren’t parked on roads and buses can get through safely.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6)  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">How effectively do Community Transport services address the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">needs of passengers in isolated communities?  How could Community Transport be improved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">See section 4.1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxi and other demand-responsive transport services?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This discrimi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nates against some of the groups who actually rely on the buses, who have not got enough money to run a car, so couldn’t afford a taxi either.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Maybe more could be done to look into taxi-share schemes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8)  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The main challenges associated with funding transpo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">rt services in isolated communities?  How can these services be made more affordable?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Judging from a public meeting about the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Wooler</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  to Newcastle bus service in March 2013, the County Council is obliged to pay for the free journeys made by pensioners,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but is given no funds for it, presumably meaning that available funds are drawn to the most used, but possibly less socially essential routes, so that people on busy urban bus routes get much more value for money and use of their pensioners’ passes than p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eople in rural areas can., but free bus travel for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> pensioners, whether rural or urban is essential – see section 4.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Do everything to make rural bus services more profitable, by effective market research and promotion, see section 3. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Funding an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> area’s rural transport as a whole network, rather than looking at individual routes separately. This only results in constant cuts, rendering the network useless for increasing numbers of dedicated passengers, and necessitating larger subsidies for the re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">maining few.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are all being exhorted to reduce emissions, but rural bus services are always being cut, despite more and more essential services and facilities being withdrawn from rural areas and centralised, so needing people to make more and longer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> journeys –</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">include funding for rural public transport as part of any centralization project or cost-benefit analysis?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Recommendations</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An obvious and easily accessible diary of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consultations, including scope and deadlines.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A clear channel to communicat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e with user groups </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e.g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  teenagers, retired, businesses for their customers and employees Their input, skills, and local knowledge would be invaluable.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Training of drivers for rural passengers, to understand that frail or vulnerable people have no alternati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve transport, and cannot be left stranded at exposed and lonely bus stops by drivers leaving early or taking shortcuts. Importantly, better understanding by managers that reliable vehicles and services are absolutely essential.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Better cooperation from Coun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cil highways departments in winter.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Make it a contractual obligation for companies operating subsidised routes to encourage profitability by facilitating market research and promotions.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#a6a6a6; font-family:Arial; font-size